    </div>
    <div class="spacer blog-content content-entryindent ">
        Thom was chewing his cud, clearly agitated over the entire situation.  I realized that with Jared spilling the beans and Thom's patience running short, I had to step in and steer the conversations.
<br/>
<br/>"Let's talk about those incentives.  Why the deadman switches on the boxes?  The smoke bombs?  The rigged logins?" I asked.
<br/>
<br/>Jared slowly inhaled.  "From what I understand, this is bigger than just Marcus and his friends stealing bandwidth and services on the school's dime.  Marcus gave me direct access to the servers to leech anything that I wanted off via secure ftp.  The boxes were peering points and used to distribute a lot of 'zero-day' items."
<br/>
<br/>"Zero-day items?  You mean like theatrical movies?  Software releases?  Music files?" I pondered out loud.
<br/>
<br/>"Yeah.  Marcus was making quite a name for himself in some circles.  Before he turned everything over to me, he seemed a bit nervous when we talked.  You know how those association groups are shutting down and prosecuting distro sites and their owners?  Well I think Marcus thought he was going to get caught eventually." Jared replied.
<br/>
<br/>"I see.  And?" I asked, leading Jared into answering the rest of my questions.
<br/>
<br/>"Right, well I didn't know the smoke charges were there until the first time I had to take a server out of service and re-image it.  Ironically enough, all of the images for these servers Marcus made himself, so all of the peering stuff just magically appeared again.  Anyway, the first time I popped the cover off of a server I got a face full of smoke and I was freaking out because the detectors up on the ceiling were beeping.  I haven't had the fire system on since." Jared admitted.
<br/>
<br/>"You turned off the da..." Thom said, flying off the table.
<br/>
<br/>"Thom, wait.  This isn't helping the situation.  Let's get all of the facts." I pleaded to Thom as he sat back down on the table with a scowl on his face.
<br/>
<br/>"I got a question." Scrap said, once again breaking the silence.  "So, you kind of knew the whole time that re-imaging these machines was just wasted cycles?  And then you'd hand off everything to the next guy that took over for you?" 
<br/>
<br/>"Well, I hadn't really thought about it that far down the road." Jared said, his eyes aimed squarely at his shoes.
<br/>
<br/>"Ok, I've heard enough.  Jared, let's go have a conversation with the Dean." Thom said, motioning Jared to exit through the door.  
<br/>
<br/>After the door was closed, I closed my eyes and exhaled.  I felt like a train accident.
<br/>
<br/>"Dude, this whole situation is freaking me out." Scrap said, drinking the last of my green tea.  "I mean, how much sense does any of this make?"
<br/>
<br/>"I can relate." I said as I rubbed my eyes.  "But the sad truth is that this type of piracy isn't exactly new or strange to school campuses.  I'm really surprised that things were so lax here.  Thom is a pretty sharp guy." 
<br/>
<br/>"It's like you always told me, Chief." Scrap said.  "People trust the people that work for them, and sometimes they trust them just a little too much." 
<br/>
<br/>I brought my bottle of green tea to my lips and attempted to take a drink from a very empty bottle.
<br/>
<br/>"You drank the last of my tea?" I asked in disbelief.
<br/>
<br/>"Hey man, sounds like you're trusting your people too much!" Scrap rattled back.
<br/>
<br/>Sometimes the teacher learns from the student.  And sometimes, you have a student like Scrap.
<br/>
<br/>=*=
<br/>Epilogue:
<br/>
<br/>Thom went on a blitzkrieg at the school.  Law enforcement and several trade associations were notified about the activities of Marcus, Jared and numerous other students.  
<br/>
<br/>Scrap scored a major consulting gig with Thom rebuilding the school's DNS architecture since all twelve servers (and numerous other items) were confiscated as evidence.   
<br/>
<br/>Lawsuits were brought against several of the students, and they were all kicked out of the university and enrolled into the school of hard knocks.
<br/>
<br/>[NOTE: I apologize for the delay in publishing the conclusion of this case file, however I had to edit it several times for content.]
<br/>
    </div>    
