            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">I want to make one thing perfectly clear=2E=2E=2E=2E=2E
Fire Protection Systems are DEADLY=2E
They Kill Fire, and don't care about life=2E
They are designed to protect the building not you=2E

You can not breath Halon you should not ever breath in any=
 heavier than air gasses which are used to force oxygen from a=
 space=2E  Halon is not being put into new construction as it has=
 been deemed dangerous=2E  Existing systems are allowed to remain=
 in place, if maintained, so you will likely run into them for a=
 long time=2E  So, if you are ever in a building that is on fire,=
 please have the good sense to get out=2E

Water systems are being put into alot of computer areas now with=
 preaction systems tied to power down backup systems that only=
 respond to fire not smoke immediately=2E  Simplified, these=
 systems are tied into smoke detectors which power down the=
 electronics and shift function to another room or another=
 facility, etc simultaneously notifying staff, police, fire=
 personnel, etc=2E and opening air bleed offs in the fire system=
 alowing water to come into the lines=2E Once the lines are charged=
 it takes enough heat to melt the fusable links in the individual=
 sprinkler heads to let the water into the heads to put out the=
 fire in the room=2E  The idea is that once you have fire burning=
 up the computers in the room there isnt much to save any way and=
 the water shouldn't do as much damage to adjoining electronics=
 any way as  there is no power to the units other than the=
 batteries, buffers, etc=2E which are usually alteast alittle=
 protected in the cases=2E Also sprinklers usually put the fire out=
 before it gets to the room with valuable computers and data in=
 it=2E

Another little caution with the above in mind, never keep servers=
 in a storage room there is usually way too much fuel for a fire=2E=
  Boxes not only burn well but they also hold large quantities of=
 oxygen=2E

</span>
		</div>
           
