<!---->

				
<span class="pubdate size11 darkgray" title="2005-06-17 15:50:00Z">Jun 17, 2005</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">1=2E  Halon 1301 is still used, but the manufacture of new Halon=
 1301/1211/etc has bee banned for several years DUE TO ITS=
 EFFECTS ON OZONE LAYER =2E  This was all part of clean air act and=
 EPA regs

2=2E  Halon is relatively safe as released (walk, don't run to=
 exit, but don't dawdle=2E  And don't go to sleep on floor, it's=
 heavier than air=2E  But Halon exposed to flames produces some=
 nasty chemicals=2E

3=2E  Recycled/recovered Halon (from decommissioned systems) can=
 still be used, but its expensive=2E

4=2E  Replacement gases are available that are ozone friendly, and=
 cheaper, with still zero contamination=2E  Inergen, among others=2E

5=2E  Dry-pipe pre-action systems are preferred for large data=
 centers (water is cheap=2E  Try get a PO through for the amount of=
 Halon needed to properly flood a one acre machine room) and=
 going dry-pipe, in addition to giving you a few minutes to=
 respond to the smoldering trash cans with flooding everything,=
 also prevent a broken/leaking pipe, or the fixture knocked off=
 the pipe by the idiot carrying the ladder without looking up=2E =
 This makes insurance companies much happier=2E

Sorry for the length

</span>
		</div>
           
